'''Main enshrined deity'''
* '''{{ill|lt=Ooyatsuhime・Tsumatsuhime|Q10935047|WD=Q10935047|lt=Ooyatsuhime no Mikoto|1=Oyatsuhime and Tsumatsuhime}}''' (Ooyatsuhime Mikoto)

'''Deity enshrined''
* Left Wakimiya: {{ill|lt=Goju Takekami|Q10881556|WD=Q10881556|lt=Goju Takekami|1=Isotakeru-no-Mikoto}} (Itakeru Mikoto)
*: Oyatsuhime no Mikoto's older brother deity, {{ill|lt=Ita-Kiso Shrine|Q11379271|WD=Q11379271|1=Itakiso shrine}} enshrined deity.
* Right side shrine: {{ill|lt=Ooyatsuhime・Tsumatsuhime|Q10935047|WD=Q10935047|lt=Miyatomatohime no Mikoto|1=Oyatsuhime and Tsumatsuhime}} (Tsumatsuhime no Mikoto)
*: The sister deity of Oyatsu Hime no Mikoto, and the enshrined deity {{ill|lt=Toumatsuhime Shrine|Q17216259|WD=Q17216259|1=Tsumatsuhime Shrine}}.As the company name suggests, our company is said to be a shrine dedicated to '''{{ill|lt=Ooyatsuhime Tsumatsuhime|Q10935047|WD=Q10935047|lt=Ooyatsuhime|1=Oyatsuhime and Tsumatsuhime}}''' (Oyatsuhime no Mikoto). Regarding Ooyatsuhime, in the 5th book of the ``{{ill|lt=Nihon Shoki|Q813935|WD=Q813935|1=Nihon Shoki}}'' Jindaiki's Treasure Sword Appearance Stage (8th Stage of the First Jindai Period), it is described that she is the daughter god of {{ill|lt=Susanoo|Q272993|WD=Q272993|lt=Susanoo|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto}} (Susanoo). Also, the older brother god of Ooyatsuhime is {{ill|WD=Q10881556|lt=Isotakeru|Q10881556|WD=Q10881556|WD=Q10881556|lt=Isotakeru/Itakeru|1=Isotakeru-no-Mikoto}}, and the younger sister god is {{ill|lt=Ooyatsuhime/Tsumatsuhime|Q10935047|WD=Q10935047|lt=Sakutsuhime no Mikoto|1=Oyatsuhime and Tsumatsuhime}} (Tsumatsu Both gods are currently enshrined at {{ill|lt=Itaikiso Shrine|Q11379271|WD=Q11379271|1=Itakiso shrine}} (Itaikiso, Wakayama City) and {{ill|lt=Tomatsuhime Shrine|Q17216259|WD=Q17216259|1=Tsumatsuhime Shrine}} (3 Ronsha shrines), respectively. These three deities are said to be the gods who brought tree seeds to Kii Province, and in Kii they are collectively known as ``''Itae Sosanjin'''' {{Sfn|Oyatsuhime Shrine (Taira)|1983|p=444-445}}. Furthermore, in the Jigihonki, ``{{ill|lt=Sendai Kojihonki|Q2716751|WD=Q2716751|1=Kujiki}}'', these three gods are said to be the gods enshrined by {{ill|lt=Kiokunizo|Q11604953|WD=Q11604953|1=Kii no Kuni no Miyatsuko}}.According to the shrine's legend, there was once a vast forest in the area around our company, and the wood was used to build houses, so it was given the divine name of ``Oya.'' According to "{{ill|lt=Ki Zoku Fudoki|Q11604964|WD=Q11604964|1=Kii Zoku Fudoki}}", the name of the enshrined place, "Udamori", came from the company's shrine complex.{{Sfn|Oyatsuhime Shrine (corner)|1985}}.

=== History ===

=== Founding ===Founding date is unknown. Shrine biography<ref group="Hara" name="Furuyu">"Shrine Furyu" ({{Harvtxt|Oyatsuhime Shrine (Shikiuchi)|1987|p=46-47}}). </ref> According to .94|N|135|12|4.67|E|region:JP-30_type:landmark|Location|name=Maezen Shrine/Kokake Shrine (first enshrined place?①)}}) It was originally enshrined in the ground, but in {{ill|lt=Emperor Suinin|Q314850|WD=Q314850|1=Emperor Suinin}}, the site was given to Ryojingu Shrine in 1616 and renamed to the ``Boar Forest'' in Shandong (Itaikeso, Wakayama City, {{Wiki coordinates|34|1 1|58.42|N|135|15|14.38|E|region:JP-30_type:landmark|location|name=Boar Forest (former enshrined place?②)}})<ref group="Note">Currently, Sansei Shrine, a shrine outside the precincts of {{ill|lt=Itaukeso Shrine|Q11379271|WD=Q11379271|1=Itakiso shrine}}, is located in Ino no Mori. </ref>{{Sfn|Oyatsuhime Shrine (corner)|1985}}. After that, "{{ill|lt=Shoku Nihongi|Q611399|WD=Q611399|1=Shoku Nihongi}}" written by <ref group="Hara" name="Taiho"/> {{ill|lt=Taiho (Japan)|Q1346269|WD=Q1346269|lt=Taiho|1=Taihō (era)}} In the 2nd year ({{ill|lt=702|Q23497|WD=Q23497|1=702}}), the three shrines of Ita-Kiso, Oyatsuhime, and Tomatuhime were transferred from Ino-no-Mori to the old shrine north of the current shrine site (Kitano-no-miya, Wakayama City). Mount Hara, {{Wiki coordinates|34|16|17.9|N|135|15|2.4|E|region:JP-30_type:landmark|location|name=Old palace (former enshrined place or ③)}}) <ref group="Note">There are currently no remains of the old palace. </ref>, and later relocated to its current location.{{Sfn|Oyatsuhime Shrine (corner)|1985}}<ref group="Note">In the Kii Famous Places Zue, ``Mt. Mihara'' is written as ``Mt. Miharayama'', and there is a different legend that it is the place where the three Ita-kami deities descended from the heavens with the seeds of wood, and from there they were divided into different shrines. </ref>.Also, "Oyatsu Hime-sha Engi" cited in "Zoku Fudoki" <ref group="Hara"> "Kii Zoku Fudoki". In </ref>, I will post a separate story that states that the three Itaige deities chose their respective places to be enshrined from Tenuki Bridge (bridge of the heavenly world) and went to various places {{ill|lt=Amakudari|Q480175|WD=Q480175|lt=Amakudari|1=Amakudari}}, but Ōyatsuhime no Mikoto chose Hirata-go, descended there, ran a palace there, and was enshrined there.

Although its relationship with our company is unknown, to the east of the shrine there is the Udamori Ruins, which is thought to be a {{ill|lt=ring-moat village|Q60995739|WD=Q60995739|lt=ring-moat village ruins|1=Moated settlements}} from the middle of the {{ill|lt=Yayoi period|Q207858|WD=Q207858|1=Yayoi period}}.

=== Outline ===

==== Ancient ====
The first reference to the history of the country as a shrine is in the aforementioned article "{{ill|lt=Shoku Nihongi|Q611399|WD=Q611399|1=Shoku Nihongi}}" {{ill|lt=Taiho (Japan)|Q1346269|WD=Q1346269|lt=Taiho|1=Taihō (era)}} 2nd year ({{ill|lt=702|Q23497|WD=Q23497|1=702}})<ref group="hara" name="Taiho">'Shoku Nihongi' article dated February 22, 702. In </ref>, it is said that the three shrines of Ita-Kiso, Oya-Tohime, and Toma-Tohime were separated."Shinsho Kaku Chofusho" {{ill|lt=Daido (Japan)|Q1373191|WD=Q1373191|lt=Daido|1=Daidō}} 1st year ({{ill|lt=806|Q30021|WD=Q30021|1=806}})<ref group="原">"Shinsho Kakuchofusho" 10 (Shinji Shoke Fudo) Daido 1st year (806). In </ref>, seven {{ill|lt=Kobe (Private)|Q11589711|WD=Q11589711|lt=Kobe|1=Kanbe (social class)}} (private houses attached to the shrine) were granted to ``Oyatsuhime Shrine'' in Kii Province {{Sfn|Oyatsuhime Shrine (Taira)|1983|p=444-445}}. Related, {{ill|lt=Shohei (Japan)|Q1324874|WD=Q1324874|lt=Shohei|1=Jōhei}} ({{ill|lt=931|Q24789|WD=Q24789|1=931}}-{{ill|lt=938|Q24794|WD=Q24794|1=938}}) "{{ill|lt=Japanese name Ruijusho|Q2702542|WD=Q2702542|1=Wamyō Ruijushō}}" is Kii Province {{ill|lt=Nakusa District|Q11415547|WD=Q11415547|1=Nagusa district}} ``Oya-go'' is listed twice in , but one of these is ``Oya-Kobe'', which means our Kobe, and this Kobe is thought to have been distributed around Udamori.

As {{ill|lt=Divine|Q11591025|WD=Q11591025|1=Shinkai (divine rank)}}, {{ill|lt=Jōkan (Japan)|Q1075635|WD=Q1075635|lt=Jōgan|1=Jōgan}} In the first year of the year ({{ill|lt=859|Q23897|WD=Q23897|1=859}}), he was elevated to the rank of Jushii (Junior Fourth Rank) along with Itagesojin and Tomatsuhimejin.{{Sfn|Oyatsuhime Shrine (Taira)|1983|p=444-445}}.{{ill|lt=extension (Era name)|Q1327274|WD=Q1327274|lt=Extended|1=Enchō}} "{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}" established in 5 years ({{ill|lt=927 years|Q30470|WD=Q30470|1=927}}) {{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}} |Engishiki Shrine Name Book|Q11064932|Shin Name Book}}, {{ill|lt=Kiokuni|Q864053|WD=Q864053|1=Kii Province}}{{ill|lt=Nagusa County|Q11415547|WD=Q11415547|1=Nagusa district}} is listed as "Oya Tsuhime Shrine" Meishin University It will be listed at {{ill|lt=Meishin Taisha|Q9610964|WD=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}} as ``Monthly Niinamatsuri|Q11516161}} and {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ninamesai|1=UNKNOWN}}, it is written that it was deposited in {{ill|lt=notebook|Q11481885|WD=Q11481885|1=Hanpei}}{{Sfn|Oyatsuhime Shrine (Taira)|1983|p=444-445}}. In ``{{ill|lt=Kinokuni Shinmecho|Q17210008|WD=Q17210008|1=Kii no Kuni Jinmyō-chō}}'', the Tenjin is listed as ``Oya Okami, the fourth rank of Jushii,'' but it is different from Itakeso Okami, who rose to Shoichii (Senior First Rank), and has an open shrine {{Sfn|Oyatsuhime Shrine (Taira)|1983|p=444-445}}.Company biography<ref group="Hara" According to name="Koyu"/>, in April of {{ill|lt=Kanji|Q1193874|WD=Q1193874|1=Kanji (era)}} 2nd year ({{ill|lt=1088|Q19463|WD=Q19463|1=1088}}), on the occasion of {{ill|lt=Emperor Horikawa|Q464267|WD=Q464267|1=Emperor Horikawa}}'s visit to {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Kumano|1=UNKNOWN}}, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=hohei|1=UNKNOWN}}, and in the first year of {{ill|lt=Choji|Q1150870|WD=Q1150870|1=Chōji}} ({{ill|lt=1104|Q12490|WD=Q12490|1=1104}}), there were {{ill|lt=Kanda|Q10855080|WD=Q10855080|1=Shinden (divine field)}} of 18{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=machibu|1=UNKNOWN}} (approximately 22 hectares) and 5{{ill|lt=machi (Unit)#Unit of Length|Q1185752|WD=Q1185752|lt=Town|1=chō}} There is a similar description in <ref group="note">'Ki Province Famous Places Zue' that it prospered due to the donation of {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=shrine land|1=UNKNOWN}} on all four sides (approximately 30 hectares). However, there is no other record of Emperor Horikawa's visit to Kumano. </ref>.

==== After the Middle Ages ====
According to the shrine biography <ref group="Hara" name="Koyu"/>, it declined after suffering from the {{ill|lt=Oei|Q1193564|WD=Q1193564|1=Daiei (era)}} uprising (first half of the 16th century) and the {{ill|lt=Tensho|Q1145058|WD=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}} military fire ({{ill|lt=Kishū Conquest#Hideyoshi's Kishu Attack|Q10855721|WD=Q10855721|lt=Toyotomi Hideyoshi's Kishu Attack|1=Battle of Kishuu}}).

According to "Kanbunki" cited in "{{ill|lt=Ki Zoku Fudoki|Q11604964|WD=Q11604964|1=Kii Zoku Fudoki}}", in the early modern period it had two towns of Kanda (approximately 2 hectares). Although this Kanda existed until after the war, it is said to have disappeared due to {{ill|lt=agrarian reform|Q208128|WD=Q208128|1=Land reform}} in {{ill|lt=Showa|Q327567|WD=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}}21 ({{ill|lt=1946|Q18610|WD=Q18610|1=1946}}). group="Note">However, in Kanbunki, it is written in the past tense, ``existed until recent times (omitted).'' </ref>. In addition, the same article mentions that the area around our company, approximately 500 {{ill|lt=stone (unit)|Q855048|WD=Q855048|lt=stone|1=Koku}}, is called the ``Kami no Ki'' and is thought to be the remains of a vast shrine complex from ancient times, but the details are not clear. In "{{ill|lt=Ki Zoku Fudoki|Q11604964|WD=Q11604964|1=Kii Zoku Fudoki}}," the company at the time was the birthplace deity of the two villages of Udamori and Kitano, but it was originally considered to have been the birthplace deity of the entire Hirata Manor to which these two villages belonged, and it is assumed that due to the separation of the Konishi, Nishitai, and Kita villages due to a conflict within the manor, only the two villages became the birthplace.In April of {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}}6 ({{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|WD=Q7757|1=1873}}), {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} |Q134917284}}, and in 1880|Q7806}}, it was promoted to {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=prefectural shrine|1=Ken-sha|WD=Q90139226}} {{Sfn|Oyatsuhime Shrine (corner)|1985}}. Also, in 1911|Q2076}}, the Soja Shrine (formerly Village Shrine) located in Miyanoshi in the northern part of Wakayama City was {{ill|lt=combined enshrined|Q11412524|WD=Q11412524|1=Co-Enshrinement}} {{Sfn|Soja Shrine Ruins (Taira)|1983|p=443}} (described later). After the war, it belonged to {{ill|lt=Shinja Honcho|Q908077|WD=Q908077|1=Association of Shinto Shrines}}.

=== God level ===
