=== About Soja Shrine, a joint shrine ===
Oyatsuhime Shrine is the Sosha Shrine (formerly Village Shrine) located in Miyanoshi, Kita Aza, Wakayama City, which was enshrined in {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}}44 ({{ill|lt=1911|Q2076|WD=Q2076|1=1911}}). This Soja Shrine is a shrine that was also called ``Soja Daimyojin'' in early modern times, but the deity it enshrines is not clear (in ``Ki Meisho Zue'' it is said that {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Nippon Takeru|1=UNKNOWN}} is enshrined) {{Sfn|Soja Shrine Ruins (Taira)|1983|p=443}}.

{{ill|lt=Enkyo|Q1183728|WD=Q1183728|1=Enkyō (Edo period)}} 3 ({{ill|lt=1746|Q7589|WD=Q7589|1=1746}}) "Nanki Shrine Record" and its subsequent "Ki Meisho Zue" indicate that the shrine name and enshrinement location is "Soja" in Kii. |Q1629088}} is close to the estimated location (present-day Fuchu, Wakayama City), so this Soja Shrine is believed to be {{ill|lt=Soja|Q1107129|WD=Q1107129|1=Sōja shrine}} in Kii Province.{{Sfn|Soja Shrine Ruins (Taira)|1983|p=443}}. On the other hand, ``Kii Zoku Fudoki'' denies this and states that the shrine that was enshrined in Nezuku Valley in Taisho Ochiai Village (present-day Ochiai, Wakayama City) was transferred from the Sōron of the Shōchu period {{Sfn|Soja Shrine Ruins (Taira)|1983|p=443}}.

=== Precincts ===
[[File:Oyatsuhime-jinja shaden.JPG|thumb|200px|right|Shrine building]]
As for the shrine building, the central main hall has an Oji-zukuri copper plate roof, {{ill|lt=facing worship|Q11415970|WD=Q11415970|1=kōhai}} is {{ill|lt=kara gable|Q977293|WD=Q977293|lt=kenkara gable|1=Karahafu}}, and {{jal {{Sfn|Oyatsuhime Shrine (Shikiuchi Shrine)|1987|p=46-47}} where {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Chigi|1=UNKNOWN}} and {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Katsuoki|1=UNKNOWN}} are placed in the ridge of ink|Shinsha}}. To keep out the fog, all four sides of the shrine are covered with wooden walls.

The side shrines on the left and right are also small-sized {{ill|lt=Nagazuzukuri|Q210684|WD=Q210684|1=Nagare-zukuri}} with copper plate roofing and have chigi and bonito trees {{Sfn|Oyatsuhime Shrine (Shikiuchi Shrine)|1987|p=46-47}}. However, the Chigi of the left wakimiya (Isotake no Mikoto) is a soto-kege, and the chigi of the right wakimiya (Miyatomatohime no Mikoto) is an inward-kege.

