=== Ritual organization ===

=== Shinto priest ===
The priesthood of Oyatsuhime Shrine was held for {{ill|lt=Tensho|Q1145058|WD=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}} ({{ill|lt=1573|Q6678|WD=Q6678|1=1573}}-{{ill|lt=1592|Q6769|WD=Q6769|1=1592}}) It is said that the Tsuchiya clan ({{ill|lt=real surname|Q11520116|WD=Q11520116|1=honsei}}: Fujiwara clan) has been hereditary since around 1987|1987|p=46-47}}.

However, in the "Kiokuni Famous Places Zue," when it was compiled in the late Edo period, the Shinto priest was the Mori clan, who claimed to be a descendant of Oyahiko no Mikoto, and the current generation is the 83rd generation from Oyahiko no Mikoto.

=== Parishioners ===
Oyatsuhime Shrine is said to be the local deity of six districts, including Udamori, where it is enshrined, Hironishi, Kitano, Nango, Nishitai, and Kita. |Q11454763}} was formed, but currently it only remains in the Nagaho district.

According to "Kii Zoku Fudoki", {{ill|lt=yabusame|Q1886157|WD=Q1886157|1=Yabusame}}, {{ill|lt=sarugaku|Q1204318|WD=Q1204318|1=Sarugaku}} and {{ill|lt=dengaku|Q3022455|WD=Q3022455|1=Dengaku}} were once held as festivals on June 1st and September 21st (both according to the lunar calendar). The same book also states that the priests of Itae-so Shrine serve during the festivals held on the last day of October and November 16th (both according to the lunar calendar), and that in October they serve food such as red bean rice, persimmon mochi, fish, and sake. It is said that a {{ill|lt=portable shrine|Q979940|WD=Q979940|1=Mikoshi}} from Itaukeso Shrine was {{ill|lt=transferred|Q11561919|WD=Q11561919|1=transferred}} to our company in November.

